postcontent: The Smith & Wesson 4013TSW with a 9 round .40 cal. 40S&W double stack magazinel was introduced in 1997 as an upgrade to the 8 round 4013 single stack model. This pistol for sale was maunfactured 6/15/1999 and is now called a Pre-rail version since in 2000 S&W added a rail to the frame for accessories which most S&W enthusiasts don't care for. The Pre-rail versions are highly sought after and now rare in this near perfect condition. The TSW (Tactical Support Weapon) features thicker full length frame rails for enhanced accuracy, and delayed unlocking to reduce felt recoil. That and a dual recoil spring set-up make this a highly controllable soft shooter for accurate follow up shots and comfortable fun at the range. Considered a compact with it's 3.5" barrel,  I found it's accuracy every bit as good as my full size pistols at all target distances with the Novak Lo-Mount 3 dot sights.Frame construction is lightweight aluminum alloy with a stainless steel slide weighing only 25.7 ozs. empty so this pistol is perfect if you want a handsome carry gun on steroids.  The action is called Traditional Double Action (TDA) which describes a longer 1st shot trigger pull which cocks the hammer, and single action short, crisp, and light trigger pull on subsequent shots. An ambidextrous safety / decocker is featured for convenience and ultimate safety. The pistol comes with 2 factory 9 round curved baseplate magazines in like new condition in a new plastic case with the original instuction manual. These pistols will also take an S&W 11 round Hi-capacity magazine with flush fit adapter which came standard at one time with the $1500 Performace Center "Shorty 40" version of this pistol. I have one pictured and available at $50 additional cost.Please email  or call / text Bill 813 . 857 . 8287 to make an offer or request more photos.

Have you heard of people dropping $1500 or $2000 on a new desert eagle 44 only to have it jam and be nothing more than a bolt action pistol? Well not this guy. It's the original model - a Mark I, with low serial number (and much nicer safety!) - estimated to be early 90's. The gun is in great shape as you can see. I am not the original owner but I have taken great care of this guy. Been fun owning but looking for a new adventure! So looking to sell this or trade it for something I don't have (I'm open to all sorts of gun trades so make an offer).As for how this shoots - very well. it's nothing like a .44 mag pistol, which I don't really enjoy. This gun is heavy, so when you shoot it the recoil is minimal - I have small frame friends that love shooting it. You can shoot this for a while and not get sore hands. It's also one of the most accurate pistols there is - if you don't know, a Desert Eagle .44 is actually more like a gas driven AR than it is your typical blowback pistol. So it's very accurate and a ton of fun. And it's in .44 not .50, which means (1) way cheaper ammo and (2) it's actually a manageable and useable gun, the .50 is really a novelty weapon.
Asking $1200. Comes with 1 magazine and 1 case. Must have valid AZ license and be 21+. CCW given preference.

postcontent: This is a Waffenwerks AK-54r, it is a rifle chambered in 7.62x54r. The rifle was made in the USA by Waffenwerks using PSL parts kits, they were modified to accept standard AK furniture rather than the traditional wooden thumbhole stock and forend. The barrel has been cut down to 16" and has a standard PSL muzzle brake. Of course, the rifle accepts 10-round PSL magazines (1 included).The rifle is in outstanding condition, I have owned it since the Spring of 2011 and have only fired 100 rounds or so. The finish is beautiful, the dimples above the magwell are very attractive, and the black Arsenal polymer furniture suits the rifle very well!This is an excellent addition or start to any AK collection (not even taking into consideration the rarity of this no longer produced firearm), the powerful cartridge is ideal for hunting or DMR applications, and it is just too much fun to shoot!
